04866nam a22005175i 9780226077987DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20102003ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226077987  a(DE-B1597)524047  a(OCoLC)746883510  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a320.8/5/09741 aBryan, Frank M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReal Democracy :bThe New England Town Meeting and How It Works /cFrank M. Bryan. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2010] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b24 line drawings, 6 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Politics and Political Economy Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: The Loneliness of the Long-Distance Democrat -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: The Methodology of Starting from Scratch -- t2. Town Meeting: An American Conversation -- t3. Democracy as Public Presence: Walking the Bounds -- t4. Attendance: The Architecture of Governance -- t5. Attendance: The Context of Community -- t6. Democracy as Public Talk: Walking the Bounds -- t7. Democracy as Public Talk: Exploring the Contexts -- t8. The Question of Equality: Women’s Presence -- t9. The Question of Equality: Women’s Participation -- t10. If You Build It, Let Them Play -- t11. The Best Democracy, the Worst Democracy -- t12. Conclusion: A Lovers’ Quarrel -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRelying on an astounding collection of more than three decades of firsthand research, Frank M. Bryan examines one of the purest forms of American democracy, the New England town meeting. At these meetings, usually held once a year, all eligible citizens of the town may become legislators; they meet in face-to-face assemblies, debate the issues on the agenda, and vote on them. And although these meetings are natural laboratories for democracy, very few scholars have systematically investigated them. A nationally recognized expert on this topic, Bryan has now done just that. Studying 1,500 town meetings in his home state of Vermont, he and his students recorded a staggering amount of data about them—238,603 acts of participation by 63,140 citizens in 210 different towns. Drawing on this evidence as well as on evocative "witness" accounts—from casual observers to no lesser a light than Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn—Bryan paints a vivid picture of how real democracy works. Among the many fascinating questions he explores: why attendance varies sharply with town size, how citizens resolve conflicts in open forums, and how men and women behave differently in town meetings. In the end, Bryan interprets this brand of local government to find evidence for its considerable staying power as the most authentic and meaningful form of direct democracy. Giving us a rare glimpse into how democracy works in the real world, Bryan presents here an unorthodox and definitive book on this most cherished of American institutions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  agovernment, democratic, new england, meeting, town, political science, poli sci, politics, small, local, research, fieldwork, academic, scholarly, textbook, college, university, higher ed, america, american, united states, usa, citizens, legislator, legislation, assembly, agenda, vermont, east coast, data, northeast, evidence, witness, questions, answers, direct, governance.1 aSolzhenitsyn, Aleksandr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist